@NODE Preferences "2.4 Preferences Program"
@{u}2.4 Preferences Program@{uu}

To  adjust  parameters  there is an  external  @{"preferences  program" SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/Multiview DOC/Prefs1.bsh"}. It  offers the
following options:

- Screen mode preferences

  Here  you  select  the  screen mode that you like best working with. To get an ASL
  screen mode requester simply click on the "+" gadget. Then you can select mode and
  size  of  the  screen.  Keep  in  mind  that  a minmum size of 640 x 400 pixels is
  required. Working  ist  most  pleasurable  with  800  x  600  and  above  (with  a
  corresponding system default font).

- Code generator options

  Here you set some default values for the program:

  a) Code generator: The shell command used for generating the code. These  commands
     are located in the "C" directory of the main program.

  b) Create main  part:  Whether a main program is to be generated in the code, that
     opens all required libraries and displays the first window.

  c) Create all function templates: Here you select whether so-called templates  are
     created, ie function stubs you only have to fill in later.

  d) Create a Makefile: Here you select whether a Makefile (not a real one) is to be
     created. This Makefile is a shell script that you have to execute  to  generate
     the code.

  e) Create Foldmarks: Here you select whether  fold marks  should be  generated for
     the functions. At this time only '///' is supported (-> GoldED).

- Save and Cancel

  cause the selected parameters to be saved or leave the preferences program. If you
  leave  the  program, no modifications will be saved. Also, new values don't change
  the behavior of the running program; to activate them  you  have  to  restart  the
  program.

@ENDNODE

@NODE WINDOWPREFS "2.5 Main program"
@{"Window Prefs" SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/Multiview DOC/WindowPrefs.bsh"}:

- Width : The width of the window as a multiple of the width of the default font.
- Height: The height of the window as a multiple of the height of the default font.
- Name  : The  name of the window, that prefixes the  functions  in the  source code
          (so you can differentiate between the windows)
- Title : The window title
- Close : If you enter CLOSEWINDOW here, the window is simply  closed, if you  enter
          anything else, a BOOL function is called that you have to supply yourself.
          If this function returns TRUE, the  window is closed, if it returns FALSE,
          it remains open.
- SizeXX: Should the window have a size gadget (bottom or right hand side or both)?
- Setup : This function is called after the window has been opened  and all  gadgets
          have been drawn.
- Refr. : A function that is called when the window's size gadget has been activated
          (and you may have to redraw something).

@ENDNODE

@NODE MAINPROGRAM "2.5 Main program"
@{u}2.5 Main program@{uu}

After starting the program you see two @{"gadgets" SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/Multiview DOC/Start.bsh"}, that let you either load an existing
file or  create a new one.  Since @{"loading" SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/Multiview DOC/Load.bsh"}  should be  self-explanatory,  we will now
discuss @{"creating" SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/Multiview DOC/Edit1.bsh"} a new GUI:

- Name of GUI: The Name of the GUI, that is prefixed when creating source  code,  so
               that  different  projects do not overwrite each other.
- Path of GUI: The path  where the  source code  is to be  generated later.  You can
               either enter a path by hand here or click on the  adjacent  symbol to
               get an ASL requester.
- Picture    : The name of the picture that is displayed when the user of your later
               program selects  "about"  from the  menu.  This path  must  either be
               absolute or relative to the  path of  your later  program.  (Best use
               PROGDIR:About.IFF or PROGDIR:pictures/about.IFF or something similar).
- About Text : If you click on "Edit" here, you get a number of string gadgets  that
               accept an "about"  text, ie a  text to  accompany the above  picture. 
               This  can for  @{"example" SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/Multiview DOC/AboutExample.bsh"}  be a  reference about  the
               program, the author and the copyright.

If you click on "Continue" now, or if you've loaded a GUI, the @{"layout window" SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/Multiview DOC/LayoutWindow.bsh"} appears
where you can start the following actions:

- @{"Application" SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/Multiview DOC/Layout2Gui.bsh"}:

  A now familiar window appears.

- @{"Window " SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/Multiview DOC/Layout2Win.bsh"}:

  Click here to add, select, delete @{"windows" LINK WindowPrefs} or to  change  their order  (since  the
  first window is opened first when creating a Makefile).

- @{"Menus  " SYSTEM "SYS:Utilities/Multiview DOC/Layout2Menu.bsh"}:

  Click here to define menu entries for the active window. There  is  a  comfortable
  requester  for  entering  menus whose usage is intuitive. Notice the arrows in the
  upper part of the window: they tell you which is the  current  mode  of  operation
  (menu,  item  or  subitem).  If  you  enter  'About' as the function, the standard
  function About() will be called which was by default associated with any window in
  versions 1.0 to 1.3.
  Thus, you can now decide yourself where this window is opened. If you  don't  want
  to  use  the  About  window,  enter an empty string to Aboutpic in the application
  preferences.  HTis  way  the  function  won't   be   generated   (well,   a   good
  compiler/linker should discard unused functions anyway).

  Notice: mutually exclusive menus are not yet supported.

